metadata.name: Why? #46
metadata.description:
The direction taken by the artwork Why? was taken when contemplating a canvas filled with what could be viewed as huge stone steps. I added the small stick people - were they climbing up or down? Where were they going? Where did they come from?
I then became interested in how subtle changes of background colour and changes of balloon colour changed the story, or the feeling of the story - ranging from bright hope to despair and futility. 

All p5.js.
The artwork is rendered at window size, use keys '2' and '3' to render larger.

metadata.name: Parametric Decoy #75
metadata.description:
The project started with the discovery of an unusual shape. Draw two parallel sine arcs and connect their opposite points. That's how you get one slice of Parametric Decoy. The shape may appear in its different phases. Sometimes elegant, sometimes awkward. Sometimes broken, sometimes symmetrical. Only connectivity stays the same.

Features:
- size: small, medium, large
- color: *several options*
- background: transparent, halftone, cutout
- distorted: no, maybe*, twisted, displaced, yes**

* "maybe" means I'm not quite sure if distortion affects visible part of the shape
** "yes" means combination of "twisted" and "displaced"

Press S to save. To download in custom size (ex. 2000px width), add &size=2000 to url, reload and press S.

Made with p5js, inspired by pop-art collages and my own geometric sketches

metadata.name: Dorado #3
metadata.description:
'Dorado' is a generative collage inspired by old book illustrations trying to get their place in this modern art world.

Textures, patterns, golden suns, insects and plants blended in a layered landscape.

· 9 main figures (2 insects, 2 flowers, and a few cactuses)
· 8 different grounds
· 8 suns
· 8 wave layers
· 2 background canvas textures

Desde Argentina, with ♥

metadata.name: fREEDOM PUNK #79
metadata.description:
Welcome to fREEDOM PUNK world.
This project is Image Composition Layers pngs.
Created with 128x128 px format.
There are 9 Layers in this project. (included transparent png files)
- Background > 130 different images
- Body > 12 different body colors.
- Eyes > 24 different eyes.
- Nose > 13 different noses.
- Mouth > 58 different mouths.
- Eyeglasses > 19 different eyeglasses. (chance of nothing is much higher)
- Hair > 133 different hair-styles and headwear.
- Cloth > 160 different clothes.
- Things (In front of the punk) > 60 different things. (chance of nothing is much higher)

So you can generate your unique fREEDOM PUNKs for sure, due to very high possibilities by the layers.

Enjoy and good luck!

metadata.name: R3B00T #115
metadata.description:
The variety of noises is infinite. If today, when we have perhaps a thousand different machines, we can distinguish a thousand different noises, 
tomorrow, as new machines multiply, we will be able to distinguish ten, twenty, or thirty thousand different noises, 
not merely in a simply imitative way, but to combine them according to our imagination.
- Luigi Russolo (The Art of Noises, 1916)

___

Generative visual, noise algorithm, organic pattern, inspired by compact disc format, transform in autonomous system, and made with code.

* Interactive feature :
- Place your mouse cursor to visual screen (canvas)
- Left click to spin the cd and play audio
- Right click to reset or back to original

* Every piece in this project have different unique audio. (All sounds created with modular synthesizer)

___

metadata.name: Gerhard #93
metadata.description:
Gerhard is a collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog on fxhash. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time. 
Richard Nadler created the textures to control composition and color. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels. This collaboration is enabled by twitter and fxhash, as the generative art community continues to explore abstraction in summer 2022 – while extreme temperatures, wildfires, ongoing conflicts and volatile markets continue to escalate. 

- Click to start a new layer of motion and color. 
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen mode. 
- Press “s” to save the current canvas. 
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

https://leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/

metadata.name: Different Intersections - Iteration 4 #55
metadata.description:
This is the culmination of a series of iterations

____ - Iteration 1
____ - Iteration 2
____ - Iteration 3

The iterations were released under the pseudonym Extracurricular Activities.

The algorithmic theme of the iterations was extensive usage of boolean operations (intersection and difference) on polygons to derive interesting composite shapes.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 1 #114
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ 0.1, ____ 0.2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.
